Mass, mesenteric, specimen for flow cytometric analysis
(T15-4083B):
CD19, CD20, CD5, and CD23-positive kappa immunoglobulin
light chain restricted B-cell population identified.
Comment:
These phenotypic findings are usually associated with
observation of proliferation centers in the tissue sample
and/or a blood involvement by monoclonal B-cell
lymphocytosis greater than 5 x 10(9) cells/L.In these
instances a diagnosis of B-cell small lymphocytic
lymphoma/chronic lymphocytic leukemia can usually be
rendered.However, if neither of these criteria is met,
correlation with clinical and morphologic findings is
required for a definite diagnosis.

paragraph.content: CT ABDOMEN PELVIS W IV CONTRAST 9/30/2015 09:10:26
PROVIDED HISTORY: Abdominal or pelvic swelling, mass, or lump, other
specified site
ADDITIONAL HISTORY: None.
COMPARISONS: None.
TECHNIQUE: Following administration of intravenous contrast material,
helical CT imaging is performed from the domes of the diaphragm to the
symphysis pubis, during the parenchymal phase of contrast enhancement.
Axial images are submitted as well as
coronal and sagittal 2-dimensional reformations.
FINDINGS: The visualized lung bases are clear. No pleural or pericardial
effusion is noted. The heart size is normal. Small low-density lesion in
the superior right lobe of the liver measures 9 mm, most likely a small
cyst. Liver shows otherwise
normal enhancement, no calcified gallstones or biliary ductal dilatation
are noted. The spleen is normal in size. The pancreas, adrenal glands
and kidneys enhance normally. There is no hydronephrosis. There is
moderate calcification of the abdominal
aorta with no aneurysm. Mesenteric and renal vessels enhance normally.
Urinary bladder is empty. There is moderate prostatic hypertrophy.
Large soft tissue mass is present in the mesentery, encasing the
mesenteric vessels, measuring 20.0 x 18.8 x 8.4 cm. This most likely
represents confluent mesenteric adenopathy. Enlarged retroperitoneal
lymph nodes are present throughout the abdomen and
pelvis as well. Adenopathy in the mesentery extends into the porta
hepatis. Largest retroperitoneal lymph node just posterior to the left
renal vein measures 3.7 x 2.5 cm. Enlarged lymph nodes are present along
the iliac vessels as well. No inguinal
adenopathy is noted. Moderate degenerative disc disease and facet
spondylosis is present in the visualized spine. No bony destructive
lesions are identified. There has been previous lower lumbar
laminectomy.
IMPRESSION: Large mesenteric soft tissue mass, combined with enlarged
retroperitoneal lymph nodes, are most likely related to lymphoma. CT
guided biopsy of the mesenteric mass could be obtained if clinically
indicated.
Circumscribed low density lesion in the right lobe of the liver superiorly
is most likely a small cyst.
Moderate vascular calcification with no aneurysm. Prostatic
hypertrophy.
